5000|$|The Saturated calomel {{electrode}} (SCE) is a reference electrode {{based on the}} reaction between elemental mercury and <b>mercury(I)</b> <b>chloride.</b> It has been widely replaced by the silver chloride electrode, however the {{calomel electrode}} has a reputation of being more robust. The aqueous phase {{in contact with the}} mercury and the <b>mercury(I)</b> <b>chloride</b> (Hg2Cl2, [...] "calomel") is a saturated solution of potassium chloride in water. The electrode is normally linked via a porous frit to the solution in which the other electrode is immersed. This porous frit is a salt bridge.|$|E
